<BYLINE>By BILL SCHULZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   You don't have to go into the woods to enjoy
viewing wildlife. You can attract a wide variety of wildlife to your
yard with a little planning and planting.
   All animals need food, water and shelter. Trees are a good place
to start. Pick varieties that produce fruits, berries or nuts and
plant different varieties that produce those foods at different
times of the year.
   The <ORGANIZATION>U.S. Forest Service</ORGANIZATION> suggests the following varieties by
region:
   South _ live oak, black gum, American holly and flowering dogwood.
   Southwest _ pinyon pine, live oak, box elder and mesquite.
   West Coast _ dogwood, hawthorne, serviceberry, black oak, <PERSON>Douglas</PERSON>
fir and Ponderosa pine.
   Your local nursery, the <ORGANIZATION>Forest Service</ORGANIZATION> or your county
agricultural extension agent all can help select varieties for your
yard.
   Birds are either fruit and seed eaters or meat-eaters.
   Orioles, vireos, warblers, chickadees, nuthatches and woodpeckers
like mature trees with large insect populations. The robin needs a
lawn with plenty of worms.
   To encourage robins and other ground feeders, water your lawn
regularly. Many species of birds love to bathe in the spray and a
well-watered lawn helps provide a good supply of both worms and
insects. It also provides mud for robins and eaves swallows to build
nests.
   If possible, let one corner of the yard grow wild with weeds and
bushes. You also can pile brush or old Christmas trees in a back
corner to create cover for both birds and small mammals, including
rabbits and ground squirrels.
   If you have alders, birches, pines, oaks, dogwoods or other
seed-producing trees, you can bet you will have squirrels.
   Seed-eating birds and flower-seeking birds often need help to
survive in the city.
   Princessfeather, asters, rockpurslanes, blessed thistle,
<LOCATION>California</LOCATION> poppies, cosmos, marigold, sunflowers, tarweed,
forget-me-not, portucala, silene, zinnas and varieties of sorghum
grow large quantiites of seeds and won't become yard pests.
   Fruit-bearing trees and shrubs are popular with birds and
squirrels.
   More than 100 species of birds will throng to raspberry,
blackberry and elderberry bushes. Other popular species are juniper,
red cedar, bayberry, mulberry, pokeberry, strawberry, sumack,
grapevines and blueberry. They will bring woodpeckers, waxwings,
cardinals, bluebirds, orioles, warblers, robins, flickers and
finches.
   Hummingbirds are the best-known flower seekers.
   They are very fond of cultivated flowers, particularly those with
red, orange or purple petals. Varieties include daylilies, lilies,
canas, morning-glories, petunias, honeysuckles, jewelweed and
trumpetcreeper.
   In <DATE>summer</DATE>, the best way to bring birds and other animals is to
provide water. In dry weather, it can mean life or death.
   A bird bath a few inches deep with the bottom sloping gradually
upward toward the edge is one of the best bets. Make sure the bottom
and the edge are rough to provide good footing. Change the water
regularly.
   Make sure it is elevated because a bird bath on the ground can be
a happy hunting ground for the local feline population.
   In <DATE>winter</DATE>, food is a magnet.
   A feeder can be as simple as a Christmas tree, decorated with
popcorn or cranberries. It's best to offer several birdfeeders with
different delicacies in each.
   Place the feeders near trees or shrubs, particularly evergreens.
Many species will stay hungry rather than fly from cover to a bare
post in the middle of the yard.
   Different species prefer different foods. Cardinals and blue jays
like sunflower seeds. Goldfinches like thistles. Sparrows and
juncoes like cracked corn. All the insect eaters, such as
woodpeckers, nuthatches and chickadees, love suet, the waste fat
from beef.
   Avoid bagged, mixed bird seed. Many brands, particularly cheaper
ones, contain varieties songbirds don't eat. Often it is cheaper to
buy one large bag each of several varieties of seed and put each
seed in a different feeder.
   Keep an area under an eave or overhanging tree branch clear of
show and scatter seed for groundfeeders.
</TEXT>
