<HEAD>Independent Film Producer Dies at 83</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   <PERSON>Lester Cowan</PERSON>, an independent producer whose
credits include the <ORGANIZATION>W.C. Fields</ORGANIZATION> comedies ``You Can't Cheat an
Honest Man'' and ``My Little Chickadee,'' died of an apparent heart
attack at 83.
   <PERSON>Cowan</PERSON>, who died at his home on <DATE>Sunday</DATE>, was production supervisor
of <PERSON>John Ford</PERSON>'s <DATE>1935</DATE> film ``The Whole Town's Talking,'' starring
<PERSON>Edward G. Robinson</PERSON> and <PERSON>Jean Arthur</PERSON>.
   Four years later he produced the first of his own films, ``You
Can't Cheat an Honest Man,'' and in <DATE>1940</DATE> made ``My Little
Chickadee,'' which also starred Mae West.
   In the <DATE>1940s</DATE>, he produced ``Commandos Strike at Dawn,''
``Tomorrow the World'' and ``The Story of G.I. <PERSON>Joe</PERSON>.''
   Cowan originated the first college course in film studies in
<DATE>1929</DATE> at the <ORGANIZATION>University of Southern California</ORGANIZATION>.
   Cowan is survived by his wife, <PERSON>Ann Ronell</PERSON>; two brothers, and a
sister.

</TEXT>
