<HEAD>Monroe Gown, Monster Mask Big Sellers at Auction</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Carrousel in 9th graf is cq.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KILEY ARMSTRONG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A siren-red, sequin-encrusted evening gown that
gentlemen preferred to see <PERSON>Marilyn Monroe</PERSON> wearing fetched <MONEY>$14,300</MONEY>
at an auction of Hollywood memorabilia.
   The dress worn in ``Gentlemen Prefer Blondes'' was sold <DATE>Friday</DATE>
to an unidentified buyer at <ORGANIZATION>Sotheby</ORGANIZATION>'s auction house. The
unidentified seller also threw in a Life magazine cover showing
<PERSON>Miss Monroe</PERSON> in the gown and <PERSON>Jane Russell</PERSON> in an identical one.
   A white lace bustier, which <PERSON>Miss Monroe</PERSON> wore under a different
gown in the <DATE>1960</DATE> movie ``Let's Make Love,'' went for <MONEY>$1,430</MONEY>. And a
black bra, of unspecified origin but inscribed with the sex
symbol's name, sold for <MONEY>$605</MONEY>.
   The beauty got some competition from a beast: a rubber monster
head from the <DATE>1954</DATE> movie, ``The Creature of the Black Lagoon.'' A
Canadian private collector got it for <MONEY>$5,610</MONEY> _ well above the
pre-sale estimate of <MONEY>$2,000</MONEY> to <MONEY>$3,000</MONEY>.
   The monster mask, in fetching sea green with red lips, is
highlighted by ``many gills to the back'' and large moles, the
auction catalog notes. When not being worn, it can be displayed in
its own clear case.
   A Salvador Dali backdrop from <PERSON>Alfred Hitchcock</PERSON>'s ``Spellbound,''
valued at <MONEY>$60,000</MONEY> to <MONEY>$80,000</MONEY>, was bought back when it failed to
make the undisclosed minimum. So was a navy blue and white checked,
cotton pinafore worn by <PERSON>Judy Garland</PERSON> in the ``Wizard of Oz,'' which
the auctioneers had hoped would go for <MONEY>$20,000</MONEY> to <MONEY>$25,000</MONEY>.
   But an anonymous buyer paid <MONEY>$6,600</MONEY> for a leather chariot toga
worn by <PERSON>Charlton Heston</PERSON> in ``<PERSON>Ben Hur</PERSON>,'' circa <DATE>1959</DATE>. Brown leather
forearm covers and a blue, 9-foot cape complete the macho ensemble.
   And <ORGANIZATION>W.C. Fields</ORGANIZATION>'s top hat from the <DATE>1939</DATE> movie, ``My Little
Chickadee,'' went for <MONEY>$3,300</MONEY> to a private collector _ a bargain,
below the estimate of <MONEY>$4,000</MONEY> to <MONEY>$6,000</MONEY>.
   The Hollywood mementos were part of Sotheby's annual Collector's
Carrousel sale that also includes toys, dolls, animated art, music
boxes and baseball memorabilia. The sale continued today.
</TEXT>
