<DESCRIPT>  BIRD; FOOD; EQUIPMENT; GUIDELINE  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  IT'S easy to get hooked on this bird feeding business. You start out with a
handful of wild-bird seed and the next thing you know you're in the kitchen
cooking up Kush Kush Crumble for the little darlings.;   And the funniest
part, the experts say, is that the birds don't really need us. They manage
just fine, thank you, without our help.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Garden  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  GUESS WHO'S COMMING TO DINNER?
HERE'S HOW TO FEED FEATHERED FRIENDS  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Cover Stories; See also related article on page 1G and 2G of this section.  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     Birds that find feeders full of seed or discover crumbs and fruit on a
feeding table will, naturally, come back for more. Still, a backyard feeder is
just one stop in a bird's search for food. Providing food doesn't make birds
totally dependent on human handouts.;   "Feeding birds is more of a benefit to
the people who are doing the feeding," says <PERSON>Ted Chandik</PERSON>, a naturalist and bird
specialist at <LOCATION>Palo Alto</LOCATION>'s Junior Museum.;   About 300 bird species are found
in the <LOCATION>Bay Area</LOCATION>; the ones most likely to appear in your yard with the least
encouragement are the house finch,; house sparrow, <LOCATION>California</LOCATION> towhee, white
crowned sparrow, hummingbird,;   the jay and cedar waxwing. The scrub jays
especially like to pig out. Chandik says jays "eat everything and anything."; 
    Black sunflower seed, white proso millet, cracked corn and wheat will
attract nearly all species of seed-eating birds.;   When you put out a simple
hanging birdseed feeder -- either homemade or store-bought -- birds that like
to perch to get their food will stop by for a snack. Sparrows, finches,
towhees, cardinals, chickadees, titmice and nuthatches all get their food this
way.;   Here are other tips on bringing birds into your yard:;   (box)  FOOD
-- Seed and grains are still the birds' favorite food. You can mix your own,
buy packaged seed mixes or merely sit back and let the garden "go to seed."
Your neighbors might hate it, but the birds will love you.;   In their book
"Feed the Birds" (<PERSON>Workman</PERSON>, <MONEY>$8.95</MONEY>), <PERSON>Helen</PERSON> and <PERSON>Dick Witty</PERSON> warn that it's hard to
evaluate packaged wild-bird seed that is widely available at supermarkets, pet
stores and garden centers. "The best mixes," the Wittys write, "will cost more
and will contain more sunflower seed or sunflower meats than any other single
component. This is why you check the label.";   Buy about one month's supply
at a time because the seed and grains can deteriorate if kept longer.;   (box)
 SETTING -- The real estate mantra -- location, location, location -- applies
to bird feeders as well. A good spot for a hanging feeder is four to six feet
above ground level, either on a post or affixed to a tree.;   Birds like to
perch in nearby shrubbery to check out the location or wait in line -- it's
called the pecking order -- for a turn at the food. The natural plantings
should be at a distance of six to eight feet -- close by for cover, but still
far enough away from feeders to protect birds from hidden cats.;   Another
option is a low feeding table. An old picnic table is just about the right
dimensions, but build a small lip around the edge of the table to keep seed
from blowing away.;   The point is to provide several types of feeding
stations in various locations to attract the widest variety of birds.;   (box)
 WATER -- It's irresistible to birds. You can find beautifully made birdbaths
at garden centers, or you can turn over a trash-can lid, fill it with water
and make the birds perfectly happy. The important part is to keep the birdbath
fresh, clean and filled.;   (box)  PLANTINGS -- Birds like a natural
environment. Evergreens are particularly enticing because they offer shelter
and safety.;   But look no further than a cherry tree full of fruit to attract
every bird within five miles. They also like quince, red mulberry, flowering
crab apple and Russian olive for fruit and berries.;   They will also flock to
bayberry, yews, viburnums, dogwood, Tartarian honeysuckle, multiflora rose (or
any that produce small hips), cotoneaster and pyracanthas.;   <LOCATION>Pyracantha</LOCATION>,
incidentally, is the berry that turns cedar waxwings and robins into
falling-down drunks. In winter after being on the shrub awhile, pyracantha
berries begin fermenting and producing alcohol. Along come the cedar waxwings
and robins to binge on the berries. "They get very, very drunk," Chandik
says.;   (box)   CATS -- Prowling cats are a real danger to birds. Chandik, in
fact, says he stopped feeding birds in his own <LOCATION>East Palo Alto</LOCATION> yard because his
cat tormented the birds. "There's no foolproof way to protect the birds from
cats," he says.;   The <ORGANIZATION>National Audubon Society</ORGANIZATION> advises keeping cats indoors
in the morning and evening when birds are feeding. And, attach a bell to the
cat's collar to warn birds.; IFYOU'RE INTERESTED; The <ORGANIZATION>Santa Clara Valley
Audubon Society</ORGANIZATION>, 22221 <ORGANIZATION>McClellan Road</ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION>Cupertino</LOCATION> 95014; phone (408) 252-3747.  </TEXT>
