<HEAD>Non-Profit Housing Group Launches Its Largest Project Yet</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto staffing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 400 construction volunteers, led in a
rousing hymn by Mayor <PERSON>Andrew Young</PERSON>, began work <DATE>Monday</DATE> to build 20
homes in five days for working but poor families.
   The effort by the non-profit Habitat for Humanity, an ecumenical
Christian organization, is named the ``<PERSON>Jimmy Carter</PERSON> Work Project''
in honor of the former president, a former <ORGANIZATION>Habitat</ORGANIZATION> board member who
will join the workers for the final three days. It is the group's
largest project yet.
   Young, also a Congregationist minister, proclaimed it ``Habitat
for Humanity Week'' and led the crew in an impromptu rendition of
``When The Roll Is Called Up Yonder.''
   ``You bring with you the spirit and love of God, and a concern
for `the least of these' _ God's children,'' Young told the
workers. ``We are willing to combine our service and our cash in
the service of Christ.''
   The three-bedroom, one-bath houses being constructed in the
<LOCATION>Edgewood</LOCATION> neighborhood will be sold at no profit, with no interest,
to 20 working families with children. Mortgage payments will
average about <MONEY>$175</MONEY> a month, including taxes and insurance.
   The new neighborhood is being built on a block of land in
southeast <LOCATION>Atlanta</LOCATION> donated by the city. Supporting the 400-odd
construction workers are another 800 volunteers handling a variety
of chores.
   Plans call for 30 more houses to be built in the <LOCATION>Cabbagetown</LOCATION>
neighborhood by <DATE>1989</DATE> and 25 more homes by <DATE>1990</DATE> in another
neighborhood. Habitat for <ORGANIZATION>Humanity</ORGANIZATION> is working to raise <MONEY>$1.5 million</MONEY>
for the first 50 homes in the <LOCATION>Atlanta</LOCATION> project.
   Young recalled that he and his wife, <PERSON>Jean</PERSON>, were able to buy a
home of their own years ago, when he worked on a small salary at
the <ORGANIZATION>Southern Christian Leadership Conference</ORGANIZATION> and she earned even
less as a teacher.
   ``Now ... it's almost impossible to afford the home, the
financing and the interest,'' he said, adding that ``never before
in the history of this country have we had such a crisis in
housing.''
   But through Habitat for Humanity, ``we can have homes with no
profit, and no interest,'' <PERSON>Young</PERSON> said.
   The effort is ``real rewarding work,'' said project director
<PERSON>Bruce Gunter</PERSON>, an <LOCATION>Atlanta</LOCATION> investments counselor and veteran Habitat
volunteer. ``This is such a motivational bunch of folks.''
   About one-third of this week's workers are in the construction
business themselves, <PERSON>Gunter</PERSON> said. ``Another third are moderately
skilled, and the other third don't know one end of the hammer from
the other.
   ``But there's work for everybody; you need some people to tote
things, too,'' he said.
   Also on <DATE>Monday</DATE>, Habitat for Humanity supporters began a
1,200-mile walk from <LOCATION>Portland</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Maine</LOCATION>, to <LOCATION>Georgia</LOCATION>. Along the way,
they plan to build 120 homes for needy families.
   <DATE>Sunday</DATE> in <LOCATION>Macon</LOCATION>, about 200 people walked a mile in 100-degree
heat to the first house built by Habitat in that central <LOCATION>Georgia</LOCATION>
city.
   Habitat for Humanity was founded in <DATE>1976</DATE> by <PERSON>Millard Fuller</PERSON>, a
millionaire businessman who, in the late <DATE>1960s</DATE>, gave away his
fortune and began working to house the poor.
   <PERSON>Carter</PERSON> served on Habitat's board from <DATE>1984-87</DATE> and continues to
work with the organization.
</TEXT>
