<CAPTION>  Photo; PHOTO: AP File Photograph; CARTER UPSET -- Habitat for Humanity's most
famous carpenter, Jimmy Carter, is unhappy with the organization for
pressuring its founder to resign as president.  </CAPTION>
<DESCRIPT>  PAST; PRESIDENT; EMPLOYMENT; END; VOLUNTEER; HOUSING; CONSTRUCTION  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  What started out as an office squabble may end up costing Habitat for Humanity
its best advertisement: volunteer carpenter Jimmy Carter.;    If Carter
doesn't stay, it could be a major blow to the 15-year-old Christian
organization that has built 10,000 low-cost homes for working poor people
around the world.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Front  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  CARTER MAY HANG UP HIS HOUSING HAMMER
GROUP'S INTERNAL SQUABBLE IRKS HIM  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     <PERSON>Carter</PERSON> has hinted that he may quit in the wake of <DATE>Monday</DATE>'s announcement by
<PERSON>Millard Fuller</PERSON>, founder of Habitat for Humanity, that the organization's board
of directors pushed him to resign as president.;    <PERSON>Carter</PERSON> has been Habitat's
leader for fund-raising and its most recognizable carpenter since <DATE>1984</DATE>,
ensuring a wave of publicity for the group any time he picked up a hammer.;   
Fuller said <DATE>early today</DATE> he doesn't believe <PERSON>Carter</PERSON> will stay unless the board
rehires him.;    "Recent decisions by the board of directors of Habitat to
force the resignation of <PERSON>Millard Fuller</PERSON> as president have been quite
disturbing to us," <PERSON>Carter</PERSON> said in a statement on behalf of himself and his
wife, <LOCATION>Rosalynn.</LOCATION>;    "Our prayers are that the board of directors will be able
to resolve the arguments," he added. "Our own personal roles in the future
will be more specifically defined by these decisions.";    <PERSON>Carter</PERSON> declined to
elaborate on the statement.;    Habitat's board chairman, lawyer <PERSON>Geoff Van
Loucks</PERSON> of <LOCATION>San Jose</LOCATION>, said the group is negotiating with Fuller to find a role
for him within the organization but without administrative responsibilities.; 
  <PERSON>Fuller</PERSON> said in a phone interview from <LOCATION>Americus</LOCATION> <DATE>today</DATE> that the board members
asked for his resignation during a meeting in <LOCATION>Portland</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Ore.</LOCATION>, on Saturday.;   
He said the controversy was prompted when he and <PERSON>Jeff Snider</PERSON>, Habitat's chief
executive officer, tried to fire a senior staff person from <LOCATION>Habitat</LOCATION>'s <LOCATION>Americus</LOCATION>
headquarters.;    He declined to identify the staffer but said the board
upheld the firing.;    <PERSON>Van Loucks</PERSON> said the board's problems with <ORGANIZATION>Fuller</ORGANIZATION>
involved his trying to run the organization while keeping up a busy travel
schedule.;    The group has more than 560 affiliates in the <LOCATION>United States</LOCATION> and
more than 100 projects in 30 foreign countries. It was honored <DATE>Monday</DATE> by
<ORGANIZATION>Housing and Urban Development</ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON>Jack Kemp</PERSON> for the building of its
10,000th home: a <MONEY>$33,000</MONEY> bungalow in <LOCATION>Atlanta</LOCATION>.  </TEXT>
