<HL> LEISURE &amp; ARTS: Even as It Burns, Yellowstone Is Reborn </HL>
<AUTHOR> Ruth Rudner </AUTHOR>
<SO> </SO>
<DATELINE> Yellowstone National Park, Wyo.  </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   We tied the horses in the shade and sat down at the edge of a meadow on <ORGANIZATION>Shallow Creek</ORGANIZATION>. 
Smoke spread along the tree-covered ridge bounding the meadow's far side. 
It appeared in isolated pockets lower down, rising softly, like morning wisps of mist over a stream. 
Suddenly flames shot up from the top of the ridge: towering orange spears of fire mimicking the shape of trees, but magnified and ugly, laced with black spumes, shrouded in thick, yellowish smoke. 
There was nothing gentle about it. 

   Yellowstone is on fire. 
Unprecedented winds and dryness have combined to fuel the fires to proportions no one could have predicted. 
"In 118 years there has never been a <DATE>summer</DATE> without rain," <PERSON>John Varley</PERSON>, the park's chief of research, told me. 

   In spite of its all-out fight, the park can manage only the direction of the fires' flanks, attacking wherever towns and other developed sites are threatened. 
It is humanly impossible to put them out. 
Even if firefighters had gotten an earlier start on extinguishing the fires, they wouldn't have had much luck. (Such attempts elsewhere in the region this <DATE>summer</DATE> have been unsuccessful.) 
Suppression will come when it finally rains or snows. 
Then, one act of nature will deal with another. 
Even now, the prime burning period is steadily shortening as the days shorten. 

   Residents of gateway towns, angered at the fires' proximity, forget, when faced with nature's power, that they have chosen to live on the edge of wildness. 
Most of these people depend on tourists for a livelihood. 
They are understandably frightened the fire will rob them of all they have. 

   While these people worry about their homes and their livelihoods, others see the fires as destructive to the earth. 
But this is too short a view of nature. 
For forests, fires bring rebirth and renewal. 

   Speaking as an ecologist, <PERSON>Mr. Varley</PERSON> says, "It's the end of one life cycle, but it's the beginning of another." 

   In <LOCATION>Yellowstone</LOCATION>, at the edge of fire, I felt present at the beginning. 
I was in the park for a five-day horsepacking trip sponsored by the <ORGANIZATION>Yellowstone Institute</ORGANIZATION>, the nonprofit adjunct to the park's interpretive programs, which, ironically, had a fire ecology class on this <DATE>summer</DATE>'s roster that was canceled (before the fires started) for lack of interest. 
The horse trip was led by outfitter and botanist <PERSON>Dick Clark</PERSON>, who had a double mission in this annual course: to honor the <LOCATION>Nez Perce</LOCATION> by retracing the route of their <DATE>1877</DATE> flight from the <ORGANIZATION>U.S. Army</ORGANIZATION>, and to teach low-impact horsepacking. 

   Because a portion of our planned route went through the Clover-Mist fire, it had to be changed. 
Revised, it was also more historically appropriate, according to <ORGANIZATION>Yellowstone</ORGANIZATION> historian <PERSON>Aubrey Haines</PERSON>. 
It took us up the <LOCATION>Pelican Valley</LOCATION>, through prime grizzly habitat, toward the Mirror Plateau, where the <LOCATION>Nez Perce</LOCATION> were known to have camped. 

   We crossed into the broad Shallow Creek drainage, west of the <LOCATION>Pelican Valley</LOCATION>, to camp near <PERSON>Fern Lake</PERSON>. 
There was smoke in the northeast, coming from the Clover-Mist fire, the largest in the park, the one now close to the towns of <ORGANIZATION>Cooke City</ORGANIZATION> and Silver Gate. 
The air smelled of smoke. 

   At certain times the air everywhere in the region smells of smoke, even in <LOCATION>Bozeman</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Mont.</LOCATION>, 90 miles north of the park, where I live. 
Sometimes, waves of smoke come billowing down a valley. 
Sometimes smoke lingers over the ridge-tops, as if the sky were covered by gray and acrid clouds, yet you turn around and the sky is deepest blue. 

   Shallow Creek runs out of <ORGANIZATION>Wapiti Lake</ORGANIZATION> just to its south. 
The lake was to have been our second campsite, but with the fire coming down the ridge, we moved back down to <LOCATION>Broad Creek</LOCATION>, about three miles from our original campsite. 
As we approached, a coyote ambled along the creek. 
Earlier, we had glimpsed elk bedded down in a far meadow and a bear at the edge of forest who rose up on two legs to see us better. 
A <ORGANIZATION>Swainson</ORGANIZATION>'s hawk soared overhead. 
Evenings and mornings, <LOCATION>Canada</LOCATION> geese flew over, honking. 

   "Shouldn't we see animals running from the fire?" someone asked. 
But that's not what animals do. 
"Bambi," it turns out, really was a fairy tale. 
While some of <ORGANIZATION>Yellowstone</ORGANIZATION>'s elk have left burning areas, none were running, and many are simply bedding down a hundred yards or so from the flames. 
Bears, too, just move aside. 
<PERSON>Mr. Varley</PERSON> told me he has never "talked to a firefighter who has seen a large, dead animal." 
Elk have been seen going into still smoldering blackened areas to lick the mineral ash. 
Some biologists speculate that the elk like those areas because the bugs, normally a horror for them at this time of year, have gone up in smoke. 
And in the wetter areas, where new growth begins sprouting almost as soon as the fire is out, elk find a fresh source of food. 

   Most of the smaller animals are burrowers who simply go underground until the fire passes. 
The reproductive parts of many plants are also safely underground, ready to grow when the fire stops. 
Lodgepole pine actually requires fire to burst open and release the seed from one of its two kinds of cones. 
After a fire, the nutrient-rich earth sprouts with a speed the shade of its former vegetation never would have allowed. 

   Until we sat at <ORGANIZATION>Shallow Creek</ORGANIZATION> watching the flames, the fire had not affected us. 
Now it entered our lives. 
For some in the group it seemed too close. 
Yet the fire's pattern is to flare up in the afternoons, and we had seen it at the height of its activity. 
It was unlikely to reach us in the time of our stay. 
The animals weren't running. 
I didn't want to either. 

   Though this <DATE>summer</DATE>'s conflagrations are on a large scale, earlier fires in the same type of habitat can offer indications of what will happen this time around. 
As it turns out, the habitat in the area of the Clover-Mist fire, with some of the park's most productive soil, is new. 
Ecologists, excited about what will happen here, anticipate an extraordinary diversity of plant life, insects, mammals and, especially, birds. 

   Fire plays a big role in the life of birds. 
Some, like goshawks, requiring old-growth forest, will take off for them, but more species will appear than leave. (Figures from past fires show about 12 species leaving, 18 appearing.) 
The century of fire suppression preceding current policy encouraged the decline of certain birds throughout the <ORGANIZATION>Rockies</ORGANIZATION>. 
For mountain bluebirds, black-backed and three-toed woodpeckers and wood phoebes, whose populations should boom in the next 10 to 20 years, fire literally is the chance of a lifetime. 
Even fish stand to benefit from the fire as nutrient-rich leafy vegetation grows up along streams and then falls in. 

   What is natural in the park is not threatened by fire. 
Normally, as was true this year, the fire season doesn't even start until baby birds have fledged and the other young of the year can get out of its way. 
Thermal features such as geysers won't burn up. 
The new growth on previously burned areas is fire-resistant. 

   We rode back to <ORGANIZATION>Shallow Creek</ORGANIZATION> the next morning, hoping to get beyond it to Mirror Lake and the Mirror Plateau. 
There was little fire activity on the ridge, beyond a few puffs of smoke. 
An occasional puff issued from the slope. 
By the time we reached a small, unnamed lake about three miles from <ORGANIZATION>Mirror Lake</ORGANIZATION>, the smoke was thicker. 
Fire blocked our way to the plateau. 

   That evening a helicopter landed in our meadow. 
Lake District <PERSON>Ranger John Lounsbury</PERSON> wanted to get word to our leader, <PERSON>Dick Clark</PERSON>, that fire was moving toward <ORGANIZATION>Wapiti Lake</ORGANIZATION> and that a new lightning strike was burning near <PERSON>Fern Lake</PERSON>, closing the trail we had taken in. 
We had one way out now, but it was the route we had planned, so we weren't inconvenienced. 
It did bring home to us that fire can cancel options. 
In the short run. 
In the long run, earth, animals and, therefore, people benefit from the renewed, vigorous and robust life the fire bears. 
It is an awesome event, this new earth being prepared for a life that comes almost at once, phoenix, rising from its own ashes. 

   For Park information, contact <ORGANIZATION>Yellowstone National Park</ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION>Wyo.</LOCATION> 82190. (307) 3447381. 
For information about the <ORGANIZATION>Yellowstone Institute</ORGANIZATION>, contact The <ORGANIZATION>Yellowstone Association</ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION>P.O.</LOCATION> Box 117, <ORGANIZATION>Yellowstone National Park</ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION>Wyo.</LOCATION> 82190. (307) 344-7381, ext. <DATE>2384</DATE>. 

   ---
   <PERSON>Ms. Rudner</PERSON> is a free-lance writer based in <LOCATION>Bozeman</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Mont</LOCATION>. 

</TEXT>
