<BYLINE>Endangered Squirrel On National Forest Land Targeted For Ski Resort
^By PAIGE St. JOHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An endangered species of flying
squirrels and a virgin stand of red spruce are in the way of a
developer's plan to turn a section of national forest into a <MONEY>$100
million</MONEY> ski resort.
   Environmentalists are mounting forces to oppose a proposal by
<ORGANIZATION>Laurel Creek Development Corp.</ORGANIZATION> to build a resort community on the
north slope of <ORGANIZATION>Big Spruce Mountain</ORGANIZATION>, which overlooks the <ORGANIZATION>Cranberry
Wilderness Area</ORGANIZATION> in eastern <LOCATION>West Virginia</LOCATION>.
   The developer is negotiating with the <ORGANIZATION>U.S. Forest Service</ORGANIZATION> to
swap another piece of forestland for the Big Spruce land.
   ``We're concerned about the precedent here, of swapping really
pristine land at the call of an out-of-state developer,'' said <PERSON>Mary
Wimmer</PERSON>, conservation chairwoman for the <ORGANIZATION>West Virginia Sierra Club</ORGANIZATION>.
   <ORGANIZATION>Laurel Creek</ORGANIZATION> officials joined with Gov. <PERSON>Arch Moore</PERSON> last week to
announce the development, which has sold 100 club memberships
already, starting at <MONEY>$15,000</MONEY> each. The governor claimed <ORGANIZATION>Laurel
Creek</ORGANIZATION> could create as many as 2,300 jobs in four years, counting
spin-off services. Building lots will cost between <MONEY>$100,000</MONEY> and
<MONEY>$500,000</MONEY>, <PERSON>Moore</PERSON> said.
   But <ORGANIZATION>Laurel Creek</ORGANIZATION> does not yet own the heart of its project _ the
top of the mountain, which has an elevation of 4,695 feet. Without
it, officials said <DATE>Monday</DATE>, the resort would have no long ski runs.
   Joined with 1,000 to 2,000 acres of land <ORGANIZATION>Laurel Creek</ORGANIZATION> already
owns, the company would create a 2,300-acre complex with two golf
courses, 32 ski runs, seven restaurants, lodges, cabins and houses.
   The mountaintop is a scarce habitat for the <LOCATION>Northern Virginia</LOCATION>
flying squirrel, which lives in only a few areas of the state.
   The rust-colored, palm-sized animals roam the woods at night,
gliding among the tree tops. The flying squirrels have disappeared
over most of their <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> range for unknown reasons, but
environmentalists blame the decline on a loss of habitat.
   The squirrels like mature red spruce stands, which are
experiencing problems in the region.
   ``The spruce decline along the whole Appalachian corridor is
very serious. It is becoming very scarce,'' <PERSON>Wimmer</PERSON> said. ``These
areas need to be set aside.''
   She said she also is waiting for the <ORGANIZATION>Forest Service</ORGANIZATION> to check the
mountain for other endangered species, including the Cheat Mountain
salamander, which lives in red spruce forests.
   Local trout fishermen also are concerned the resort would
pollute Day Run, a trout stream, and in turn hurt the <LOCATION>Williams
River</LOCATION> and the <LOCATION>Cranberry River</LOCATION>, which flows through
nationally-protected wilderness areas.
   And conservationalists have another problem _ the way the matter
has been handled.
   While the development was announced publicly last week, it was
revealed that the corporation began talking privately with the
<ORGANIZATION>Forest Service</ORGANIZATION> a year ago a land swap.
   ``We feel there's been way too much work done without local
input on this,'' <PERSON>Wimmer</PERSON> said.
   <PERSON>Richard Trochlil</PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION>Forest Service</ORGANIZATION> office in <ORGANIZATION>Elkins</ORGANIZATION> said
<ORGANIZATION>Laurel Creek</ORGANIZATION> had made no firm trade offers. To be acceptable, the
land must match Big Spruce's stands of red spruce, he said.
   He said there was no available figure on how much of the
mountain would be cut for ski slopes.
   He said the mountain is not a wilderness area, and that three to
four Forest Service-supervised logging operations already are
cutting trees in the national forest.
   <ORGANIZATION>Laurel Creek</ORGANIZATION> officials did not return repeated telephone
messages left this week.
</TEXT>
