<HEAD>Forest Service Authorizes Telescopes on Mount Graham</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARTHUR H. ROTSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TUCSON, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The <ORGANIZATION>U.S. Forest Service</ORGANIZATION> said <DATE>Thursday</DATE> it
had authorized the <ORGANIZATION>University of Arizona</ORGANIZATION> to build three telescopes
on <ORGANIZATION>Mount Graham</ORGANIZATION> after determining construction wouldn't harm an
endangered squirrel.
   The <ORGANIZATION>Justice</ORGANIZATION> and Agriculture departments signed off on the
project, saying a study by the <ORGANIZATION>U.S. Fish</ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION>Wildlife Service</ORGANIZATION> had
satisfied worries that the observatory, which would include the
world's most powerful telescope, would threaten the habitat of the
<LOCATION>Mount Graham</LOCATION> red squirrel.
   ``As soon as we can we'll sign relevant construction documents
and obtain our permit,'' said university spokesman <PERSON>Steve Emerine</PERSON>.
He said work would begin as soon as possible.
   <ORGANIZATION>Maricopa Audubon Society</ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON>Robin Silver</PERSON> said in <LOCATION>Phoenix</LOCATION>
that attorneys for environmental groups opposed to the <MONEY>$200 million</MONEY>
project would be in court by <DATE>Friday</DATE> <TIME>morning</TIME> seeking a temporary
restraining order.
   Expert witnesses in the hearing ``will now include members of
<ORGANIZATION>Congress</ORGANIZATION>, the Fish and <ORGANIZATION>Wildlife Service</ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION>Forest Service</ORGANIZATION> biologists
and the <ORGANIZATION>General Acounting Office</ORGANIZATION>,'' Silver said.
   Rep. <PERSON>Morris K. Udall</PERSON>, <LOCATION>D-Ariz.</LOCATION>, and other members of the <LOCATION>Arizona</LOCATION>
delegation oppose construction of the telescopes without further
study. <PERSON>Udall</PERSON> was out of town and couldn't be reached for comment.
   A survey earlier this year determined there were fewer than 150
of the half-pound rodents _ one of 25 genetically distinct
subspecies of the red squirrel _ scurrying over the mossy,
spruce-covered slopes of 10,500-foot Emerald Peak.
   The <ORGANIZATION>Justice Department</ORGANIZATION> had been reviewing a recommendation by a
team at the Fish and <ORGANIZATION>Wildlife Service</ORGANIZATION> that another biological study
be undertaken before construction begins on the mountain 125 miles
northeast of <LOCATION>Tucson</LOCATION>.
   Emerine said the university would work with the <ORGANIZATION>Forest Service</ORGANIZATION>
and Fish and <ORGANIZATION>Wildlife Service</ORGANIZATION> to create a buffer zone around the
construction site so as not to disturb the squirrel.
   A statement from <PERSON>George M. Leonard</PERSON>, associate chief of the
<ORGANIZATION>Forest Service</ORGANIZATION>, said further consultations would be made if the
project resulted in the deaths of more than six squirrels in any
one year.
   The university proposed the construction of the observatory in
<DATE>1984</DATE>. Its partners include the <ORGANIZATION>Smithsonian Institution</ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION>Max
Planck Observatory</ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION>West Germany</LOCATION> and the <ORGANIZATION>Vatican Observatory</ORGANIZATION>.
   In <DATE>March</DATE>, <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> District <PERSON>Judge Alfredo C. Marquez</PERSON> granted the
request of environmental groups and issued a four-month injunction
barring construction on <ORGANIZATION>Emerald Peak</ORGANIZATION>. But an appeals court in <LOCATION>San
Francisco</LOCATION> overturned the delay in <DATE>May</DATE>.
   <ORGANIZATION>General Accounting Office</ORGANIZATION> investigators testified before a
congressional hearing in late <DATE>June</DATE> that the squirrel's fate had
become more precarious since the <DATE>1988</DATE> congressional act that
authorized construction of the telescopes.
   A springtime count indicated there were between 132 and 146 of
the squirrels left on the mountain, their only habitat.
</TEXT>
