<HEAD>Hugging Allegations Keep Some at Habitat at Arm's Length</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELLIOTT MINOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMERICUS, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Habitat for <ORGANIZATION>Humanity</ORGANIZATION>'s founder is keeping
some people at arm's length while its leaders and backers struggle
with allegations that he improperly hugged and touched five female
workers.
   The allegations have sent founder <PERSON>Millard Fuller</PERSON> into near exile
and put an uncharacteristic strain on Habitat, a strongly religious
organization that uses ``sweat equity'' to build housing for the
poor around the world. It has a <MONEY>$50 million</MONEY> budget and 100,000 <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION>
volunteers, including former President <PERSON>Carter</PERSON>.
   ``It has been a situation that has caused a lot of pain because
we're all very close,'' said <PERSON>Claire Williams</PERSON>, spokeswoman for
Habitat's board.
   Fuller, who says he only touched the women in exuberant shows of
friendship, still can be found chatting with Habitat volunteers.
But he avoids the headquarters and is careful how he greets people.
   ``I no longer initiate hugs,'' he said in an interview <DATE>Thursday</DATE>.
``When charges of this nature are made, it's very difficult to
defend yourself.''
   No criminal charges have been filed against Fuller, 55. The
women have not been identified, and their allegations have been
described only in general terms.
   <PERSON>Geoff Van Loucks</PERSON>, chairman of <ORGANIZATION>Habitat for Humanity International
Inc.</ORGANIZATION>, has said the women alleged ``nothing criminal'' when they
complained to a Habitat chaplain.
   ``They claim inappropriate comments and inappropriate hugging
and touching. They've never, ever claimed anything more. Nor is
there a hint of anything more,'' Van <PERSON>Loucks</PERSON> said. ``Let me make
clear there was no sexual intercourse.''
   Fuller, who founded Habitat with his wife, <PERSON>Linda</PERSON>, also is to
move his base of operations to <LOCATION>Atlanta</LOCATION>. Because of a reorganization
that was planned before the controversy, he has gone from executve
director to president.
   The organization also hired the <ORGANIZATION>Mennonite Conciliation Service</ORGANIZATION>
to counsel Fuller and the women. But there have been divisions over
whether enough has been done.
   <PERSON>Tim O'Donnell</PERSON>, who recently finished a 2{-year term at the
headquarters, said he received a harsh handwritten note from <PERSON>Carter</PERSON>
after <PERSON>O'Donnell</PERSON> complained about the way the board investigated the
claims against Fuller.
   ``You are either completely foolish or trying to sabotage the
work of Habitat,'' said a copy of the letter provided by <PERSON>O'Donnell</PERSON>.
``Attacking <PERSON>Millard Fuller</PERSON> and the board of directors is a
reprehensible act. ... Don't make it more difficult for those
trying to resolve the problem.''
   <PERSON>Carter</PERSON> spokeswoman <PERSON>Carrie Harmon</PERSON> declined to comment on the
letter's authenticity.
   <PERSON>Carter</PERSON>, who annually spends at least a week working at Habitat
homebuilding projects, has publicly defended Fuller. In a recent
interview with <ORGANIZATION>The Atlanta Journal-Constitution</ORGANIZATION>, he said the nature
of the accusations upset the ``extremely conservative'' board
members, who then were ``overly inclined to condemn'' Fuller.
   Fuller still is a visible presence in <LOCATION>Americus</LOCATION>, a town of 16,000
about 10 miles from <PERSON>Carter</PERSON>'s hometown of <LOCATION>Plains</LOCATION>. Fuller now works
out of his law office, a few blocks from <LOCATION>Habitat</LOCATION>'s headquarters.
   Fuller, a former millionaire who gave away his money in <DATE>1970</DATE> and
founded Habitat in <DATE>1976</DATE>, said he has apologized to all five women
and met personally with three of them.
   ``When someone says they have been offended, the common-sense
thing and the Christian thing is to seek reconciliation,'' he said.
``I'm not trying to paint myself as a perfect person who has been
victimized. I obviously was not sensitive enough in my relations
with these women.''
   Back at Habitat headquarters, <LOCATION>California</LOCATION> businessman <PERSON>Jeff
Snider</PERSON>, who arrived <DATE>Thursday</DATE>, has taken over as executive vice
president in charge of operations.
   As a reporter arrived, a male employee greeted a female
receptionist with a hug.
   <PERSON>Ms. Williams</PERSON>, the board spokeswoman, said, ``We've seen progress
in the two or three months it's been going on.''
   But <PERSON>O'Donnell</PERSON> said the controversy has taken a toll at the
organization, which has over 450 projects in the <LOCATION>United States</LOCATION>,
<LOCATION>Canada</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Australia</LOCATION> and more than 80 in 26 developing countries.
   ``People almost feel they have to take sides,'' he said. ``I
know of a handful of people who have left because of the
situation.''
   Fuller said he wants to focus on the future.
   He said his promotion to president and the opening of a Habitat
office in <LOCATION>Atlanta</LOCATION> are part of a long-range plan developed last year
that just happened to coincide with the controversy. Fuller said he
helped pick <PERSON>Snider</PERSON> to run Habitat.
   ``Because of the timing, it appears that I'm being run out of
town,'' said Fuller. ``I want us to get on with the business of
building houses for the needy.''
</TEXT>
