<HEAD>Thousands Visit New `Rain Forest'</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 7th graf ``Zoo Business'' with 2 grafs to CORRECT
Saturday attendance figures and add Sunday figures. Picks up 8th
graf pvs ``The four-acre...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID SIMPSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   <PERSON>Willie B.</PERSON> and the other gorillas in a new ``rain
forest'' at <LOCATION>Zoo Atlanta</LOCATION> seemed to take it in stride when the
general public was admitted to the attraction for the first time.
   Thousands of people streamed into the <ORGANIZATION>Ford African Rain Forest</ORGANIZATION>
after a ribbon-cutting ceremony <DATE>Saturday</DATE> to strain for a look at
<PERSON>Willie B.</PERSON>, the zoo's biggest star, in the lush open-air habitat
which replaced the cage he occupied for 27 years.
   The 450-pound gorilla, now about 30 years old, immediately came
to the edge of a restraining moat to strut for the crowd; once, he
ran down a grassy slope, drawing applause.
   On each side, across moats, two families of gorillas recently
brought to the zoo kept a greater distance from onlookers but
remained mostly in the open and not in their shelters.
   Zoo Director <PERSON>Terry Maple</PERSON> said the gorillas, while physically
separated, have interacted in the 2{ weeks they have been together.
   ``They're vocalizing, they're beating their chests, they're
moving this way and influencing the others,'' <PERSON>Maple</PERSON> said. ``The
behavior of animals is enhanced by the presence of others.''
   Zoo Business Manager <PERSON>Dennis Baker</PERSON> said a record for paid
attendance at the zoo was set <DATE>Saturday</DATE>, and broken <DATE>Sunday</DATE>. <DATE>Sunday</DATE>'s
crowd was 11,860, with 10,893 paid, passing the mark of 8,522 set
<DATE>Saturday</DATE>, when there were also nearly 5,000 free admissions.
   The zoo's best attendance was 17,000 in <DATE>1986</DATE> when there was free
admission to celebrate <PERSON>Willie B.</PERSON>'s birthday, but the record paid
attendance before <DATE>Saturday</DATE> was about 7,400, <PERSON>Baker</PERSON> said.
   The four-acre, <MONEY>$4.5 million</MONEY> rain forest, boosted by <MONEY>$1 million</MONEY>
donated by the <ORGANIZATION>Ford Motor Co.</ORGANIZATION>, is the centerpiece of a renovation
of the 99-year-old zoo, dubbed one of the 10 worst in the country
by the <ORGANIZATION>U.S. Humane Society</ORGANIZATION> only <DATE>four years ago</DATE>.
   Three gorilla families, including the two already present, are
being provided by the <ORGANIZATION>Yerkes Regional Primate Research Center</ORGANIZATION> at
<LOCATION>Atlanta</LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION>Emory University</ORGANIZATION>.
   The exhibit includes an adjacent aviary, featuring birds from
the same areas of <LOCATION>West Africa</LOCATION> inhabited by the gorillas.
   It is the second of 10 habitats planned; a flamingo habitat
opened first. Next year, <ORGANIZATION>Maple</ORGANIZATION> said, the zoo will present an east
African savanna, featuring lions and elephants and including a pool
deep enough for an elephant to immerse itself.
</TEXT>
